In TypeScript, you can achieve a type system that acknowledges the theoretical possibility of a value having multiple types, but restricts it to only one type in practice, by using type guards. Type guards are a way to conditionally narrow down the type of a variable based on certain conditions.

Here's an example to illustrate this concept:

```typescript
type MetaType<T> = <T extends number>; // Abstract type that can be any number

type PracticedType<T> = T;

// Type guard to restrict the value to a specific type
type PracticedMetaType<T> = MetaType<T>;

// Type guard to restrict the value to a specific type
type PracticedPracticedType<T> = PracticedType<T>;

// Example usage
const value1: PracticedMetaType<number> = 42; // This is allowed
const value2: PracticedPracticedType<number> = 42; // This is allowed
const value3: PracticedPracticedType<string> = "hello"; // This is not allowed
```

In this example:

- `MetaType<T>` is an abstract type that can be any type, including numbers, strings, etc.
- `PracticedType<T>` is a type that can only be used to specify types that extend `MetaType<T>`.
- `PracticedMetaType<T>` is a type guard that narrows `MetaType<T>` to types that can be used in practice.
- `PracticedPracticedType<T>` is a type guard that narrows `PracticedType<T>` to types that can be used in practice.

By using these type guards, you can create a type system where you acknowledge the theoretical possibility of a value having multiple types but restrict it to only one type in practice.

